rule.description:
When using String.join() with an empty string separator, use string
concatenation instead for better readability and simplicity.

Instead of: String.join('', new List < String > {'a', 'b', 'c'});
Use: 'a' + 'b' + 'c';

Version: 1.0.0

property.value:

//MethodCallExpression[
	@MethodName = 'join'
	and @FullMethodName = 'String.join'
	and .//LiteralExpression[@String = true() and (@Image = "''" or @Image = '""' or string-length(@Image) = 0)]
	and .//NewListLiteralExpression
]

rule.example:

// Violation: String.join with empty separator
String result = String.join('', new List<String> {'a', 'b', 'c'});

// Valid: Use string concatenation
String result = 'a' + 'b' + 'c';
